Simple simulation

Define data

library(simstudy)

def <- defData(varname = "C", formula = .4, dist = "binary")
def <- defData(def,varname = "A", formula = "-2 + 2*C", variance = 2, dist = "normal")
def <- defData(def, varname = "Y", formula = "5 + 2*C + 2*A", variance = 2, dist = "normal")

def
##    varname       formula variance   dist     link
## 1:       C           0.4        0 binary identity
## 2:       A      -2 + 2*C        2 normal identity
## 3:       Y 5 + 2*C + 2*A        2 normal identity

Generate data

set.seed(383743)
DT <- genData(1000, def)

DT
##         id C          A           Y
##    1:    1 0 -2.0378672 -0.06030641
##    2:    2 1  2.3697939 12.49548410
##    3:    3 1  0.6572423  9.76613140
##    4:    4 0 -4.8420748 -4.14773495
##    5:    5 1  0.9798642  6.85207752

##  996:  996 0 -0.3459693  4.95418613
##  997:  997 0 -0.3236121  4.35949410
##  998:  998 1 -0.6497596  9.68466537
##  999:  999 0 -0.9596235  1.80557290
## 1000: 1000 1  1.2542694  8.43596583

Look at data

p <- ggplot(data = DT, aes(y = Y, x= A)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = factor(C)), size = 1) +
  theme(panel.grid.minor = element_blank()) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("#CC6677","#4477AA"))
p

Fit models

lmfit1 <- lm(Y~A, data = DT)
summary(lmfit1)
##

lmfit2 <- lm(Y~A + C , data = DT)

Look at model fits

ggplot(data = DT, aes(y = Y, x= A)) +
  geom_point(size = 1) +
  theme(panel.grid.minor = element_blank()) +
  geom_abline(intercept = coef(lmfit1)[1], 
                slope = coef(lmfit1)[2],
                size = 1)

Correct lines:

p + 
  geom_abline(intercept = coef(lmfit1)[1], 
              slope = coef(lmfit1)[2],
              size = 1) +
  geom_abline(intercept = coef(lmfit2)[1], 
              slope = coef(lmfit2)[2],
              color = "#CC6677", size = 1) +
  geom_abline(intercept = coef(lmfit2)[1] + coef(lmfit2)[3], 
              slope = coef(lmfit2)[2],
              color = "#4477AA", size = 1)
